How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time were sold in most cases only to the socialist blockade, since travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore took vacations at the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) in Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972 when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime moved west and the travel of Czech tourists was then quite limited.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist block (or, also the Czechs) would not be allowed to travel freely and individually even by socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was impossible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those days, but one should get to the corner with a bag of sleep and spend the whole night, or have "good known" in the agency.
Still didn't get it.
The so-called "change promise" which was the condition for Western travel was not granted to the "politically unliquidated" people who could not travel in absolute terms.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not a free convertible currency and, without an exchange guarantee, it was not possible to obtain resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
Most of the Czechs had their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses that the Czechs would buy. This custom still persisted.
The way in which the Czechs travel has suffered has been a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 it was not going to take vacations in the RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the current favorite destination, Croatia, was unable to travel freely until 1989, because it was then part of Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of the 1990s, visa exemption was imposed to travel to the neighbouring States of Western Europe, resulting in a huge oil of short-term visits, particularly in Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see the heat of the excursions to the West, all the world wanted to see it for at least one moment.
For example, in Paris, checkout groups slept in the parks in the shops of the camp, since our incomes from then did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the checks at that time was taking with you food (conservatives, embuteds, etc.) to store.
Another important moment was the introduction of the conversion of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy free Western currency.
Our standard of living also increased the average wages with him, which resulted in an increase in travel demand around 1997.
With the increase in the demand for travel, the agencies began, from 1997 on a regular basis, to prepare the journeys using charter flights, which made the prices of the journeys considerably lower compared with the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts on passenger volume.
At the end of the 90th century, the Czechs had already traveled almost all developed countries, except the United States, which made our journey even more simple.
Another interesting moment in post- revolutionary tourism history occurred in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Chequia to an exotic country, and it went to Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter flights with Czech tourists have made distant and warm countries. This winter will already fly directly from Chequia to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries currently visit them about 100,000 Czechs per year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post- revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States eliminated the visas for Czech tourists, with which our country became among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent over 15,000 Czech crowns per head on trips to the foreign country, including expenses at the station.
