If the signs sending the floor were observed, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand wells per flood season in the Metropolitan Valley region of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Najera, researcher at the UNAM University of Chemicals (FQ), who ensured that if the construction and maintenance of an asphalt floor process is the appropriate one, the wells could be reduced in quantity or, even, completely removed.
At its conference A technological opinion of the baches, based on the International Year of Chemicals, made it known that the laboratory at its task develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to that of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrra Najera believed that this type of modified waste could be used in areas where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of waste.
He explained that the asphalt, the most heavy part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, one of high molecular weights, called asphaltenes, and the other of low molecular weights, called maltenos, which together give the floor its viscosity.
The viscose behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade presents a almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes fractured, added.
The previous means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform, but that it is changing during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the expert in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City in most of them are covered by flexible floor coverings, consisting of six layers of materials, of which the last three are involved in the asphalt.
Among the most surface layers is the asphalt folder, followed by small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that forms the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By passing vehicles and generating efforts, this allows forces to disintegrate very well into the floor.
If it was about modified asphalt, it would be even better distributed, the chemical engineer thought.
On the asphalt folder, it was enough to place a last layer called a rotary folder, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e. an arena which is also bathed in asphalt.
As is the case with the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, there must be more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
As part of the floor that will receive and distribute efforts, the rolling folder also requires proper thickness and the material of what is being done must be cared for.
The climate, particularly the humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, in particular water, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the ground is wet, the water is scattered inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this creates a reforestation of all layers of the floor and therefore the formation of floors.
In the process of training a bache, he said, the first thing to waste is the film of rotation and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Investigators also explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the training of decks and therefore the thickness of each floor deck must always be in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that they are carried out, in order to avoid frequently falling.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to research and work on asphalt, for example asphalt emulsion, which in other countries are already in the market and allow for easy repair and no need to use high temperatures.
