The North Stream, new Russian gas entrance door in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea, has already been in service.
Gas must be provided to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated in the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, in the opening of the North Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly communicates, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
In symbol, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart of the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have turned together the wheel of the valve controlling Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, every year it will reach 27.5 million cubic metres of additional Russian gas in Western Europe through a first wave of 1.224 km from San Petersburg to the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be concluded at the end of 2012 allowing a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, it is already mentioned the possibility of building a third tube by the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion at the time of this huge work presents a win area.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, North Stream will allow for gas supply directly to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
In fact, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening its access to Western European markets.
At the end of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, in support of the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been aware, within just five years, of moving its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," François Fillon confirmed during the launch of the gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the large gas sector contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the Gazprom directives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-covered steel to protect it from the anchor of the ships.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them by caution," says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to eliminate the protection measures for the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs as 242 Eiffel Towers and is not interrupted in all its length: either by valves or by maintenance stations.
A control platform was envisaged in the waters of Sweden, but the project officials rejected it when they saw that the Swedish were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to be established permanently at sea in front of its shores.
"In case of accident, we'll break the gas step in less than a minute," needs Jens Müller.
In the case of escape, gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
However, constructionists consider it unlikely that a flight will be produced, as it has been foreseen that it will have a flight every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the gas pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot drawn by a ship carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device orbiting the inside of the pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it is introduced into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of a meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides precise data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without any type of repair.
Gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
At first it's 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined their forces in order to carry out this project.
The lead company is Gazprom, which has 51% of the participation.
She was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5 per cent each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez (9 per cent).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
