Disillusionment?
"No", says Eric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
"The progress made 15 years ago is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, it's still too much to do."
It should be noted that disabled persons continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
It is common to have a more advanced age: 37% is over 50 years old (about 17% medium).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% have not completed the primary school and only 10,000 of the 2.3 million students in higher education are disabled.
Finally, the long-term balance is very wide among them: 53% for disabled people, compared to 38% of the average.
In other words, there are many issues that are particularly difficult to return to the working world and that "consisting the cause of the problem", said Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
