In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality progresses but is too slow.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Company Association for the City indicated that the respondents had "a level of knowledge about low disability", with "extensive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are very far from the objective of hire 6% of disabled workers, with the aim of being set out in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures of 2008, a ratio of 2.6 per cent is reached.
"We now reach around 3 per cent," said Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for returning contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishment "submitted to this import" as well as the amount disbursed has decreased between 2007 and 2011, ranging from 59 000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, has generated a great pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of the companies that have between 20 and 49 employees have employees with disabilities in their model, compared with 82 per cent of the companies between 100 and 199 workers.
